The article discusses how Reverend Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.'s work to fight racial discrimination and inequality in America remains unfinished. It highlights Dr. King's vision of a "Beloved Community" that transcends differences and promotes unity. The article acknowledges Dr. King's contributions to the Civil Rights Act and the Voting Rights Act and emphasizes the need to continue his work by passing legislation such as the John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act and the Freedom to Vote Act. The article also mentions the administration's efforts to achieve economic justice, improve access to healthcare, and promote equity and opportunity. It concludes by calling for reflection on the progress made and the work that still needs to be done to create a better America for all. The article ends with President Joe Biden proclaiming January 16th as the Martin Luther King, Jr., Federal Holiday and encouraging Americans to participate in civic and service projects in honor of Dr. King.